The Vice President of the United States, Mike Pence, delivered a speech in Warsaw, Poland, to commemorate the 80th anniversary of the outbreak of World War II. He praised the courage and resilience of the Polish people during the war, highlighting the atrocities committed by the Nazis and the Soviet Union. Pence also acknowledged the sacrifices made by American and other Allied forces in the fight against totalitarianism. He emphasized the importance of remembering the causes of the war and the struggle between right and wrong, good and evil. Pence referenced Pope John Paul II's visit to Poland in 1979, which sparked a revolution of conscience and eventually led to the fall of the Berlin Wall and the end of the Soviet Union. He concluded by reaffirming the alliance between the United States and Poland and their commitment to freedom and self-determination.